{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"compacted_at":1782526623865214001,"compiled_state":{"alias":"peak-fir-hilt","assignee":"","author":"Joe Oakhart","bridge_alerts":[],"comments":[{"author":"Joe Oakhart","body":"DE-RISKING FINDING from epic A's experiment (story A3, review_skeleton): the plan-review CRITERION prompts (src/rebar/llm/reviewers/plan_review_*.md) are NOT in the workflow prompt CATALOG that load_catalog()/prompt_ref_exists() resolve (catalog = code-quality, completion-verifier, security, spec-alignment, tests, ticket-quality). They are loaded only by the bespoke gate's registry via get_prompt('plan-review-<id>'). CONSEQUENCE for B: a workflow cannot reference a plan-review criterion via batch.criteria[].prompt and pass lint until those prompts are wired into the workflow catalog. This is the concrete 'criteria-library mirrors the prompt-library' wiring B must do (so the criteria are editable + eval-attached through one library). A3 used catalog ids in its skeleton to prove the SHAPE offline; B adds the plan-review prompts to the catalog as a migration prerequisite. (A3 FIXED a sibling flaw in A: the linter now existence-checks a batch step's nested prompts, which the agent-step path missed.)","timestamp":1782414477060576001},{"author":"Iso Tester","body":"EPIC FOLLOW-UP (per user): once plan-review is migrated to the workflow engine (B2) and cut over (B5), CONFIRM whether the stale-attestation stopgap in CLAUDE.md (the 'claim immediately after a passing review-plan, before committing other work' guidance + the don't-run-review-plan-concurrently-with-HEAD-moving-work corollary, both stopgaps for bug worm-folly-barge: any intervening commit staleness-invalidates the plan-review attestation at claim) is still necessary. If the migration (or the code-drift-invalidation work in boil-golem-veto / ADR 0002) has made it unnecessary — e.g. the workflow path's attestation is no longer whole-HEAD-bound — REMOVE the stopgap from CLAUDE.md as part of this epic (likely folded into B5 cutover or B6 cleanup). Add a checklist item to whichever story lands the cutover.","timestamp":1782443274098414001},{"author":"Iso Tester","body":"PASS-1 REVIEW (G6 — approach soundness) of story B4 (Planned-trace parity harness). One mechanism-completeness finding; rationale + approach-selection affirmed.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (G6 criteria passed):\n- FITNESS-FOR-PURPOSE / positive rationale (G6.2, G6.4): The \"Why\" states a strong, correct positive rationale — assert PLANNED-trace parity, NOT result parity, because \"the review is LLM-dependent and variable.\" This is the right proxy-avoidance: it validates that both implementations ISSUE the same plan rather than trusting equivalent LLM output. PASS.\n- APPROACH SELECTION (G6.3): The central design choice (planned-trace parity vs. the obvious alternative, result/output parity) is defensible and well-argued; the offline FakeRunner corpus over a diverse scenario set (container/leaf, overlays, code-grounded, oversize, missing-AC) is at-least-as-good on testability + blast-radius (no live calls/credentials, CI-able) than a live golden-output approach. The pre-escalation-only assertion correctly tolerates non-deterministic size-ladder escalation. No clearly-superior alternative missed. PASS.\n\nFINDING (G6.1 mechanism correctness — incomplete trace-capture seam):\nThe \"What\"/\"Scope\" describe the harness as running \"via the Fake runner\" (singular) and lean on Epic A's `PlannedTraceRunner` (an `AgentStepRunner`, src/rebar/llm/workflow/trace.py:22). But per this epic's own design note (docs/design/batch-runner-seam.md:149-157, 169-173 — the critique's MAJOR 4), the planned trace MUST be assembled from TWO offline-fakeable capture points: (a) the batch's `rebar.llm.Runner` for the FINDER calls and (b) the engine's `AgentStepRunner` for the Pass-2 verify step. The finder is `passes.pass1_chunk(runner: Runner, ...)` (src/rebar/llm/plan_review/passes.py:186-212) — it drives a `rebar.llm.Runner` DIRECTLY, NOT an `AgentStepRunner`; D3 (batch-runner-seam.md:74-81) confirms the production runner owns its own injectable `rebar.llm.Runner` and the seam's `agent_runner` is intentionally unused. Consequence (batch-runner-seam.md:155-157): \"the batch's internal finder calls are NOT visible to the engine's generic `PlannedTraceRunner`/dry-run — they're traced one level down.\" As written, B4's mechanism could be implemented to capture only the `AgentStepRunner` seam, which would assert parity on a trace MISSING the finder calls — i.e. the prompt-id + intended-model + call-mode events that ARE the parity payload (epic AC3). The plan should make the dual-seam capture explicit so the implementer wires BOTH a fake `rebar.llm.Runner` (finder/criteria events) AND the `PlannedTraceRunner`/`AgentStepRunner` (verify event) and concatenates them into the ordered planned trace it diffs.\n\n- [ ] Make explicit that the planned-trace harness captures at BOTH seams — a fake/tracing `rebar.llm.Runner` injected into the production batch runner (for the finder/criteria calls, which are NOT visible to the engine's `AgentStepRunner`-level `PlannedTraceRunner`) AND the engine `AgentStepRunner` seam (for the Pass-2 verify step) — and that the asserted trace is the ordered concatenation of both; otherwise the harness diffs an incomplete trace missing the finder events that are the parity payload.\nlocation: B4 \"What\"/\"Scope\" sections; src/rebar/llm/plan_review/passes.py:186; docs/design/batch-runner-seam.md:155-173\ncriteria: G6","timestamp":1782448076363148001},{"author":"Iso Tester","body":"PASS 1 review — criterion T1 (prior-art / novel-architecture justification) for plan **B5: Cut the claim/close gates over to the workflow path (signing intact)**.\n\n**Result: PASS — no findings.**\n\nBoth bright-lines that fire here (a *migration*, and a *security/signing* surface) are well-grounded in prior art and reuse an existing substrate, so T1 is satisfied:\n\nAffirmations:\n- **T1(a) prior art considered, not reinventing.** The plan is an explicit decomposition story (B5) of epic `peak-fir-hilt`, building on B2/B3/B4. ADR 0003 (`docs/adr/0003-workflow-as-gate.md`, Status: Accepted) already establishes the \"workflow-as-gate\" pattern and names B5 verbatim as \"the epic's later cutover story\" that \"adds the gate-side helper\" + signing. The plan converges onto the *already-built* engine workflow path (`src/rebar/llm/workflow/gate_ops.py`, `gates/completion-verification.yaml`, the parity scaffolding) rather than inventing a new orchestration mechanism — anti-fragmentation, not a novel architecture.\n- **T1(b) novelty justified vs. established approach (anti-repackaging / Rule-of-Three).** No novel pattern is introduced by B5; the workflow-as-gate shape is the established, reused contract (ADR 0003 \"Reused by B2\"): B3 walked the skeleton, B2 followed for plan-review, B5 cuts over. The bespoke orchestrator + direct-agent path is being *retired onto one substrate*, which is convergence, not repackaging.\n- **T1(c) capability assertions resolved.** The load-bearing claim — that the gates can dispatch through the engine workflow path with byte-compatible signing — is verifiable from the tree: the workflow path exists (`gate_ops.py` thin adapters over `rebar.llm.completion`), the signing surface the plan commits to preserve is the existing `signing.py` (canonical `(ticket_id, manifest)` HMAC payload + `key_id` fingerprint + manifest prefixes), and ADR 0003 explicitly defers signing to this cutover (\"The workflow does not sign … Cutover + signing is the epic's later cutover story (B5)\"). No unverified \"library supports X\" assertion is left dangling.\n\nNo coaching checklist items for T1.","timestamp":1782497538779089001},{"author":"Iso Tester","body":"FORCE_CLAIM: plan-review gate bypassed by user approval — no plan-review attestation was verified. Reason: \"Epic container status-tracking claim. Bypassing the plan-review attestation per user direction: the epic's attestation is UNSCOPED (no file_impact -> whole-HEAD freshness) so it re-stales on every commit during active multi-PR epic work (worm-folly-barge residual); re-reviewing a partially-complete epic is also low-value (woozy-pea-kin). Audited bypass.\".","timestamp":1782518937805879001},{"author":"Iso Tester","body":"FORCE_CLOSE: close gate(s) bypassed by user approval — no completion/signature attestation was signed. Reason: \"Epic B migration COMPLETE + shipped: all 10 deliverable children signed-closed (B1/B2/B3/B4/B5/B6/B-DM/B-UX/B-RETIRE + tepid-bus-pomp fix); B-RETIRE merged (#50) — workflow is the sole plan-review+completion gate (bespoke run_review + B4 harness + gate_engine flag removed). The 2 open children (super-plant-liver root-cause bug, toy-kink-ire metrics task) are FOLLOW-UP work, not migration deliverables; re-homing reverts due to a concurrent store writer (reconciler re-applying the Jira epic-link), so --force. Follow-ups remain open + tracked.\". Session: f7d12b43.","timestamp":1782526622131910001}],"created_at":1782371099945480001,"deps":[{"link_uuid":"ac718ea1-44f9-41ea-8774-acf9ab2a079a","relation":"depends_on","target_id":"5766-fe6f-83d0-4252"},{"link_uuid":"4eac26a3-ad38-408d-8226-7b52227c025d","relation":"relates_to","target_id":"6f2d-4221-26de-48cc"},{"link_uuid":"dfbc132c-a689-4f3c-926a-f354c19d191e","relation":"relates_to","target_id":"2541-0fbd-84e6-46d6"},{"link_uuid":"a95a1381-0c22-4363-b458-9b88eebcc99a","relation":"blocks","target_id":"961b-a3ff-63e4-465f"},{"link_uuid":"8f78b62a-1e94-45ad-afdb-1b878534b0c2","relation":"relates_to","target_id":"4e70-0cd4-0d04-4d31"}],"description":"# Migrate the LLM gates onto the workflow engine\n\n## Context\n\nSecond of the two epics split out of soupy-spool-revel (6f2d) per the brainstorm (session logs\nboom-demon-jug ad3f + this design session). Depends on epic A (sage-votary-logic, 5766) which adds\nthe conditional-overlay and delegating-batch constructs the plan-review pipeline needs. Today the\nplan-review gate is a 707-LOC bespoke orchestrator (orchestrator.py, ThreadPoolExecutor fan-out)\nand verify_completion is a direct single-agent call (completion.py) — LLM gate logic lives OFF the\nunified engine substrate. This epic moves both onto the engine, validated by PLANNED-TRACE PARITY,\nand removes the throwaway sample workflows so only real workflows remain.\n\n## What\n\n- **Migrate plan-review onto the engine.** Re-express the 4-pass pipeline as an engine workflow:\n  overlay-resolved criterion-set -> `batch` finders -> aggregate `prompt` verify (ONE call) ->\n  `uses`/`branch` decide -> `prompt` coach; DET P1-P8 as a `uses` precheck. Supply the PRODUCTION\n  batch-runner by extracting the gate's sizing.py (adaptive batch + size-ladder + budget cap +\n  shed + fingerprint checkpoint) behind epic A's batch-runner seam.\n- **Migrate the completion verifier onto the engine.** It fits EXISTING concepts (no new\n  constructs): `uses`(deterministic child-closure+signature precheck) -> `prompt`(agentic, one\n  call) -> `uses`(reconcile/normalize) -> `uses`(sign). It is the simpler walking-skeleton migration.\n- **Planned-trace parity validation.** Run BOTH the bespoke and the workflow implementations in\n  parallel and assert PLANNED-TRACE parity — NOT result parity (the review is LLM-dependent and\n  variable). The planned trace is the ordered set of intended execution events:\n  [DET-check-id | (criterion/prompt-id, INTENDED model, call-mode agent|1-shot) | deterministic-step-id].\n  Parity is asserted on the PRE-ESCALATION planned trace, tolerating runtime size-ladder escalation\n  divergence. Run OFFLINE via the FakeRunner/FakeAgentRunner seam (no live calls) over a diverse\n  scenario corpus, so edge cases are tested exhaustively and cheaply (CI-able). Capture the\n  INTENDED/selected model (the fake echoes model=None), not the runner's echoed field.\n- **Remove the sample stubs.** Delete the throwaway example workflows (examples/code_review.yaml +\n  the templates.py scaffold per Joe's selection) once the migration lands; preserve forwarding\n  shims / public API for anything still referenced. KEEP epic A's demo workflow as the unused\n  visual-editing refinement sample.\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- Code-review migration (the real code-review reviewer is its own open epic; it will be updated\n  when these workflow changes land — not migrated here).\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- plan-review and completion-verification run on the ONE workflow-engine substrate (their prompts\n  in the engine prompt library), validated by offline planned-trace parity against the bespoke\n  implementations; only real workflows remain (samples removed).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] plan-review runs as an engine workflow (overlay-resolved criteria -> batch finders ->\n      aggregate verify -> decide -> coach; DET P1-P8 as a `uses` precheck), with the production\n      batch-runner extracted from sizing.py behind epic A's seam.\n- [ ] verify_completion runs as an engine workflow using existing step kinds only\n      (uses->prompt(agentic)->uses->uses); no new constructs needed.\n- [ ] A PLANNED-TRACE parity harness asserts the bespoke and workflow implementations issue the\n      same planned trace (same prompt-id + intended model + call-mode + deterministic steps),\n      pre-escalation, over a diverse OFFLINE scenario corpus (FakeRunner; no live calls); it runs in CI.\n- [ ] The bespoke orchestrator path is cut over to the workflow path behind the gate(s) once parity\n      holds; the close/claim gates keep working (signed verdicts/attestations intact).\n- [ ] The throwaway sample workflows (examples/code_review.yaml + templates.py scaffold) are removed\n      per Joe's selection; forwarding shims/public API preserved for anything still referenced;\n      epic A's demo workflow is retained as the visual-editing refinement sample.\n- [ ] End state: exactly two real LLM workflows (plan-review, completion-verification) + the one\n      retained sample; `make lint` + the full test suite pass.","env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","file_impact":[],"last_status_env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","parent_id":null,"parent_status_uuid":"a9178c20-7bda-44df-bced-afbdae6cb3ae","preconditions_summary":{"status":"pre-manifest"},"priority":2,"reverts":[],"signature":{"algorithm":"HMAC-SHA256","author":"Iso Tester","head_sha":"985f0fa2da033e36f6fef10c39449b7f931d4778","key_id":"412fa5372ad877e0","manifest":["plan-review: PASS","ticket: 72d5-79ec-9e2e-4a2b","material: 8787bfa111815ff9","model: claude-opus-4-8","runner: pydantic_ai","blocking: 0","advisory: 10","regver: ac0403957dc03495"],"signature":"d605291c72c08effb4a97ef41edda91e5955e35d7e77f38455c573d67347b30f","signed_at":1782509656033080000},"status":"closed","tags":[],"ticket_id":"72d5-79ec-9e2e-4a2b","ticket_type":"epic","title":"Migrate plan-review + completion-verification onto the workflow engine (planned-trace parity; remove sample stubs)","verify_commands":[]},"source_event_uuids":["b3762f12-e7b1-4c40-846b-e673bc44f2cd","ac718ea1-44f9-41ea-8774-acf9ab2a079a","4eac26a3-ad38-408d-8226-7b52227c025d","dfbc132c-a689-4f3c-926a-f354c19d191e","60a93167-cf45-4135-a1be-65839c9e4b01","b5838a6d-4525-447a-8729-5c8cee1fd5fc","13e3d08d-c58b-4156-a0d1-f32ce1699309","b672b63e-2890-4694-9038-223974ed6ac1","a95a1381-0c22-4363-b458-9b88eebcc99a","77aed99d-ba0d-4ce5-b31d-3dc4299e8b29","8f78b62a-1e94-45ad-afdb-1b878534b0c2","f5ffa42b-c885-4b13-a4d1-42cf54321cd6","df5fa667-d566-4e0b-b409-b56adde67d3d","281f27d8-d701-465b-96bb-860d367ad078","c11af571-746e-4429-a3ae-48c9f28ddeed","8089244a-a596-4529-a562-cfef99082422","c74f8c35-ba19-439e-af84-c1d7562a207c","c4189951-eb6c-4aba-b968-071ea4264e7b","a9178c20-7bda-44df-bced-afbdae6cb3ae","0121f37b-ae6f-45bc-be37-7a8782ec8e41"]},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"SNAPSHOT","timestamp":1782526623865214001,"uuid":"5a266c07-b3e9-4259-9882-bba482ad8309"}